               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431127-name-488" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-488" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-488" type="surname" value="MARKS"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-488" type="given" value="SOLOMON"></interp>SOLOMON MARKS</persName>
                  </hi>, <hi rend="italic">plate-glass dealer</hi>, 55, <hi rend="italic">Hounds ditch.</hi> This glazier's dia<lb></lb>mond is mine. On the 17th of Nov., about three o'clock, I saw it safe, and missed it about five minutes after—a boy came into my shop with something to sell—the diamond was then safe, and the moment he was gone I missed it—the prisoner was not with him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431127-name-489" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-489" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-489" type="surname" value="WENTWORTH"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18431127-name-489" type="given" value="NICHOLAS"></interp>NICHOLAS WENTWORTH</persName>
                  </hi>, <hi rend="italic">assistant to Mr. Luff, pawnbroker, Crown-street, Finsbury.</hi> On the 17th of Nov., about half-past three o'clock 'in the after<lb></lb>noon, the prisoner offered this diamond in pledge—I asked whose it was, and where he came from—he said, "From No. 6, Worship-street"—I took down the direction, and went there—it was a very large, respectable house—I in<lb></lb>quired for the name he gave, and could find no such person—on my way back I saw sergeant Roberts, gave him information, and he came and took the pri<lb></lb>soner—he said he bad been sent by his father.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18431127-name-490" type="witnessName">
